Chapter 13: The Backdoor
The golden dome of the Perimeter Shield roared as it solidified, a wall of pure, compressed energy that turned the night sky into a bruised honey color. It didn't just block physical passage; it hummed with a "Purge" frequency designed to incinerate any unauthorized Essence that touched it.
"Ren, the wall is closing!" Mira screamed. They were skidding across the wet grass of the north field, the scent of ozone so thick it felt like breathing needles.
"Don't slow down!" Ren’s eyes were fixed on the shimmering gold. In his vision, the shield wasn't a solid wall. It was a waterfall of falling gold numbers, a constant stream of 'If/Then' statements.
[Target: Academy Aegis-01]
[Integrity: 100%]
[Status: Invincible]
"There!" Ren pointed to a spot where a massive power conduit rose from the ground to feed the shield. "The refresh rate! Every 0.004 seconds, the shield's polarity flips to prevent overheating. There’s a gap in the logic!"
"I can't see a gap, Ren! I just see a wall of death!"
"Trust me!"
Ren grabbed Mira’s Resonance Staff, his fingers sinking into the wood. The silver mark on his hand bled into the staff, turning the white light into a jagged, flickering grey.
[Skill Trigger: Source Code Redirection]
[Syncing Sound-Wave Pulse with Shield Refresh Rate...]
[0.003s... 0.002s...]
"Now!"
Ren slammed the staff into the base of the golden wall.
THWUMP.
The sound wasn't a crash; it was a silent vacuum. For a fraction of a second, a hole the size of a doorway flickered into existence—not by breaking the shield, but by convincing the shield that this specific space was already empty.
They lunged through.
The sensation was like being pulled through a straw. Ren felt the "Project Architect" folder in his jacket nearly tear away as they tumbled onto the cracked, salt-stained asphalt of the Old City ruins outside.
Behind them, the golden dome snapped shut.
Ren lay on his back, gasping for air. The silver glow in his eyes faded, leaving them stinging and dry.
"We're... we're out," Mira whispered, staring back at the Academy. From the outside, the school looked like a glowing marble trapped in a jar. Searchlights were still crisscrossing the grounds, but they couldn't see through their own shield.
"They’ll be out here soon," Ren said, pushing himself up. He felt a deep, hollow ache in his chest.
[Mana: 0/10]
[System Note: Your 'Local Cache' is corrupted. Seek shelter to stabilize.]
"Let's get to the ruins," Mira said, helping him stand. "The Scavengers have tunnels near the old subway. The Association's drones lose their signal in the deep-level Void-rot."
They moved into the shadows of the skyscrapers, the skeletal remains of the world before the Gates. After an hour of navigating through rusted steel and grey dust, they found a collapsed maintenance shed.
"We need to stay here for a few hours," Ren said, sliding down the wall. He pulled the leather-bound folder from his jacket.
"Is that it?" Mira asked, sitting across from him. "The truth about the school?"
Ren opened the folder to the final page—the one he hadn't seen in the library. There was a photo clipped to it. It was a picture of Professor Aris and a man with a blurred face, standing in front of a massive, black gate.
Final Entry: The Fail-Safe.
If Subject Ren achieves 'Administrator' status prematurely, the Association must trigger 'The Great Deletion'. The Academy is not a school; it is a detonator. If we cannot control the Architect, we will erase the city to ensure the Void does not gain a physical core.
Ren felt the blood drain from his face. "It's not just a school, Mira. It’s a bomb. They didn't build it to train hunters. They built it to keep the Administrator contained. And if I leave... or if I get too strong..."
"They'll blow the whole place up," Mira finished, her voice trembling. "With everyone still inside. Jax... all the students..."
[Notification: 1 New Message from 'The Administrator']
[Message: 'The clock is ticking, Ren. Do you save yourself, or do you save the 'Data' inside the cage?']
Ren looked at the silver mark on his hand. It was pulsing with a dark, violet light now—the color of the 'Downlink' he had stolen.
"I'm not running away," Ren said, his voice turning hard. "I'm going to learn how to defuse it."
Ren now knows the stakes. He is the Architect, but his very existence is a trigger for the city's destruction.
